{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514167"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12286"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12286"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.05,0.52,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114345"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4808"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96345"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1795"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"10772"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45582"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114345"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman is brought to the clinic by her family with concern over a two week history of severely agitated mood. Her mother reports that her daughter talks incessantly, her sleep is markedly decreased, that she believes she is the most beautiful girl in the town and people should always respect her. In this agitated mood she has physically attacked three of her family members who would not believe her. Such behaviour is most uncharacteristic of her usual self. She has had multiple similar episodes of severe mood agitation in the past 2 -3 years, each lasting for around a fortnight with a gap of around 4-6 months between episodes. During the initial episodes she was admitted to hospital and the doctors diagnosed her as having manic episodes of bipolar disorder. During the interval time she shows some ongoing symptoms but far less severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, according to her mother, her daughter also has been behaving \u0022weirdly\u0022 over the past 2-3 years even when not agitated or manic, believing that all the people of her town are secretly trying to kill her. The daughter also describes having a friend who talks to her all the time even though no one can see her. Her family confirm that there is no friend present and that they do not hear anyone talking. She has left her job since her symptoms began and confines herself to her room, sometimes does not eat food, wears dirty clothes for long time periods and forgets to comb her hair - all of which is not like her usual self. These symptoms are continuous since her symptoms have started and do not come in the form of episodes. On examination she is very agitated and there are no focal neurological signs. A urine drug analysis is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schizophrenia","Schizophreniform","Schizoaffective disorder","Bipolar I","Delusional disorder"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is presenting with long standing signs of schizophrenia: persecutory delusions (people of town trying to kill her), auditory hallucinations (a friend who talks to her while her family denies presence of any such person), disorganised behaviour (confined to the room, not eating, wearing dirty clothes and not combing hair) and episodes of major mood disturbance. The presence of current and past superimposed episodes of severely agitated mood, increased talking, decreased sleep and grandiosity (most beautiful girl in town and people should respect her) reflect attacks of mania, ending spontaneously after which her symptoms of schizophrenia persisted. This history is characteristic of a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eschizoaffective disorder,\u003C/strong\u003E which is characterised by episodes of major mood disturbances (mania or depressive disorders) with concurrent symptoms of schizophrenia and when the major mood symptoms abate there are persisting schizophrenic symptoms that last for at least two weeks without any mood disturbance being present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the presence of delusions, auditory hallucinations, disorganization of speech and behaviour and sometimes diminished emotional expression lasting for more than six months. While depressive symptoms are common (particularly during acute illness and its recovery) they are not prominent or severely persistent and there is no mania.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophreniform\u003C/strong\u003E disorder has the same symptoms of schizophrenia but the symptoms have lasted for at least one month but less than six months (symptoms persisting beyond six months lead to a diagnosis of schizophrenia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar I disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by the presence at one or more times of episodes of mania. These episodes may also be preceded by or occur between episodes of major depression. Bipolar I Disorder is less often associated with symptoms like delusions, hallucinations or disorganisation but when psychotic features can sometimes be present they are usually mood congruent and will last only during the episode of mood disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusional disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the presence of only delusions and no other symptoms that one sees in schizophrenia. A delusion is a false fixed belief. In delusional disorder, hallucinations are not prominent and there are no disorganisation symptoms or bizarre behaviours present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schizoaffective disorder is characterized by signs of schizophrenia with mood disorders like depression or mania."],"references":["Wy TJP, Saadabadi A. Schizoaffective Disorder. [Updated 2022 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96345"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12286"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96345"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T18:26:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T18:27:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4808"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114345"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite